      <h2>The Problem: Standards at Scale</h2>
<SketchContainer sketchId="hierarchy" height="var(--space-4xl)" mobileHeight="var(--space-3xl)" ariaLabel="Self-building organization tree" />

      <ShibuiContent id="org-architecture.the-problem-standards-at-scale.p1">
	<span slot="entry">
		<p>I built a single repository that governs every other repo in the organization. It pushes out shared CI pipelines, security scanning, contributor guidelines, and AI agent configs so that no individual project has to reinvent those wheels. One source of truth, inherited everywhere.</p>
	</span>
	<span slot="elevated">
      <p>
        Every multi-repository organization faces the same entropy: standards drift, security configurations diverge, and contributor onboarding becomes a per-repo archaeology exercise. <ShibuiTerm term="Conway's law" definition="The 1968 observation that system designs inevitably mirror the communication structures of the organizations that build them" /> predicts this — organizations that design systems are constrained to produce designs which mirror their communication structures, and when those structures are fragmented across dozens of repositories, fragmentation is the inevitable output.<Cite id={1} author="Conway, Melvin E." title="How Do Committees Invent?" source="Datamation" year={1968} /> The open-source world has known this for decades. Raymond's analysis of the bazaar model revealed that even decentralized projects require institutional infrastructure — mailing list conventions, patch formats, release protocols — to avoid collapsing under their own coordination costs.<Cite id={2} author="Raymond, Eric S." title="The Cathedral and the Bazaar" source="O'Reilly Media" year={1999} /> GitHub's special <code>.github</code> repository mechanism offers a solution: a single repository whose contents — workflows, templates, governance documents, AI configurations — are inherited by every other repository in the organization. This project takes that mechanism and builds a comprehensive organizational operating system on top of it, governing {vitals.repos.total} repositories across {vitals.repos.orgs} organizations from a single source of truth.
      </p>
	</span>
</ShibuiContent>
<button class="shibui-bridge" type="button">This section goes deeper &#8594;</button>

